<paragraph id="A7543694FF85FF8996C2FB9CDF1934C7" blockId="1.[173,660,805,1730]" lastBlockId="1.[707,1194,194,853]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8996C2FB9CDA183275" bold="true" box="[197,352,1044,1065]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Comparisons.</emphasis>
A m o n g t h e 
<collectingCountry id="DFFC7604FF85FF899404FB9CD9413275" box="[515,569,1044,1065]" name="United States of America" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">U S A</collectingCountry>
f a u n a, 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8996AAFBA6DA0C3218" box="[173,372,1070,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chuckbellamyi">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8996AAFBA6DA0C3218" box="[173,372,1070,1092]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. chuckbellamyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8996AAFBC1D9703202" authority="Knull, 1954" authorityName="Knull" authorityYear="1954" box="[173,520,1097,1119]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robigo">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8996AAFBC1DA043203" box="[173,380,1097,1119]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Acmaeodera robigo</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C37A4B65FF85FF899781FBC1D9703202" author="Knull" box="[390,520,1097,1118]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" pagination="27 - 30" refId="ref2024" refString="Knull, J. N. 1954. Five new North American species of Buprestidae (Coleoptera). Ohio Journal of Science 54 (1): 27 - 30." type="journal article" year="1954">Knull, 1954</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, known only from 
<collectingRegion id="652FF876FF85FF8996E3FBECDA633225" box="[228,283,1124,1145]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Texas</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="652FF876FF85FF899756FBECDAC03225" box="[337,440,1124,1145]" country="United States of America" name="Oklahoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Oklahoma</collectingRegion>
; however, it is immediately separated from that species by the form of the ninth elytral interval, which is highly elevated from behind the umbone, making the elytra appear laterally flared on the apical half when viewed from above. The ninth interval is less distinctly elevated on 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF89970BFA8BDA1F3345" authorityName="Knull" authorityYear="1954" box="[268,359,1283,1305]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robigo">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF89970BFA8BDA1F3345" box="[268,359,1283,1305]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. robigo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the elytra do not appear at all flared apically. 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899781FA95D9EB336F" box="[390,659,1309,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chuckbellamyi">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899781FA95D9EB336F" box="[390,659,1309,1331]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Acmaeodera chuckbellamyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899416FAB0DAD23334" authority="Nelson, 1994" authorityName="Nelson" authorityYear="1994" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubrovittata">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899416FAB0DA653334" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Acmaeodera rubrovittata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C37A4B65FF85FF899720FADBDAD23334" author="Nelson" box="[295,426,1363,1384]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" pagination="272 - 282" refId="ref2090" refString="Nelson, G. H. 1994. Six new species of Acmaeodera Eschscholtz from Mexico (Coleoptera: Buprestidae). The Coleopterists Bulletin 48 (3): 272 - 282." type="journal article" year="1994">Nelson, 1994</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from southern 
<collectingCountry id="DFFC7604FF85FF89944CFADBD9EB3334" box="[587,659,1363,1384]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="652FF876FF85FF8996B4FAE6DA7033DF" box="[179,264,1390,1411]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="652FF876FF85FF899716FAE6DA2733DF" box="[273,351,1390,1411]" country="Mexico" name="Morelos" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Morelos</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion id="652FF876FF85FF899796FAE6DAAA33DF" box="[401,466,1390,1411]" country="Mexico" name="Puebla" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Puebla</collectingRegion>
), which also exhibits a well-developed ninth elytral interval. This character is also seen in 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF89975EFA2AD9F733E4" authority="Knull, 1960" authorityName="Knull" authorityYear="1960" box="[345,655,1442,1464]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cazieri">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF89975EFA2AD96D33E4" box="[345,533,1442,1464]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Acmaeodera cazieri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C37A4B65FF85FF89941BFA2BD9F733E4" author="Knull" box="[540,655,1443,1464]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" pagination="6 - 7" refId="ref2056" refString="Knull, J. N. 1960. A new subspecies of Acmaeodera quadrivittata Horn (Coleoptera: Buprestidae). Ohio Journal of Science 60 (1): 6 - 7." type="journal article" year="1960">Knull, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8996AAFA35D970338E" authority="Cazier, 1940" authorityName="Cazier" authorityYear="1940" box="[173,520,1469,1491]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parkeri">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8996AAFA35DA03338F" box="[173,379,1469,1491]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Acmaeodera parkeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C37A4B65FF85FF899781FA35D970338E" author="Cazier" box="[390,520,1469,1490]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" pagination="17 - 29" refId="ref1945" refString="Cazier, M. A. 1940. New North American Acmaeodera, with synonymical and miscellaneous notes on other species (Coleoptera: Buprestidae). The Wasmann Collector 4 (1): 17 - 29." type="journal article" year="1940">Cazier, 1940</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899410FA35DAF533B1" authority="Fisher, 1949" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1949" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruricola">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899410FA35DB8733B1" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Acmaeodera ruricola</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C37A4B65FF85FF89970DFA50DAF533B1" author="Fisher" box="[266,397,1496,1517]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" pagination="327 - 351" refId="ref1984" refString="Fisher, W. S. 1949. New buprestid beetles from Mexico, Central and South America, and the West Indies. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 99 (3240): 327 - 351." type="journal article" year="1949">Fisher, 1949</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8997CBFA5FDA22305B" authority="Waterhouse, 1882" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1882" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setosa">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8997CBFA5FD9EB33B1" box="[460,659,1495,1517]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Acmaeodera setosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C37A4B65FF85FF8996AAFA7ADA22305B" author="Waterhouse" box="[173,346,1522,1543]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" refId="ref2124" refString="Waterhouse, C. O. 1882. Biologia Centrali-Americana: Insecta. Coleoptera. Serricornia: Buprestidae, Volume 3, Part 1. (F. D. Godman and O. Salvin, editors). London, UK." type="journal volume" year="1882">Waterhouse, 1882</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, being more strongly developed in the latter three species. Differences between 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8996AAF9AFDA233061" box="[173,347,1575,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chuckbellamyi">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8996AAF9AFDA233061" box="[173,347,1575,1597]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. chuckbellamyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899793F9AFD9533061" authorityName="Nelson" authorityYear="1994" box="[404,555,1575,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubrovittata">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899793F9AFD9533061" box="[404,555,1575,1597]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. rubrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
include a slightly broader, more flattened appearance (although the L/W ratio does not differ); the ninth elytral interval slightly more elevated basally; the front margin of the clypeus broadly, shallowly, evenly emarginate (in 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899797F924D95A309E" authorityName="Nelson" authorityYear="1994" box="[400,546,1708,1730]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubrovittata">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899797F924D95A309E" box="[400,546,1708,1730]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. rubrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it appears broadly, slightly triangularly emarginate); the sutural intervals of the elytra more distinctly elevated; the coarser punctation of the elytral striae; the last abdominal ventrite more coarsely, densely, discretely punctate; and the red-orange color pattern of the elytra extending well over the sides almost completely to the lateral margins. In this last character, 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899550FEF3DF7A37CD" box="[855,1026,379,401]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chuckbellamyi">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899550FEF3DF7A37CD" box="[855,1026,379,401]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. chuckbellamyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
more resembles 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8994C4FE1ED86637F0" authorityName="Knull" authorityYear="1954" box="[707,798,406,428]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robigo">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8994C4FE1ED86637F0" box="[707,798,406,428]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. robigo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF89955EFE1ED89C37F0" authorityName="Nelson" authorityYear="1994" box="[857,996,406,428]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubrovittata">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF89955EFE1ED89C37F0" box="[857,996,406,428]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. rubrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<specimenCount id="B1EDFD1DFF85FF899215FE1FDFF437F0" box="[1042,1164,407,428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" type="generic" typeStatus="paratypes">19 paratypes</specimenCount>
of the latter that were examined, the red-orange pattern does not reach the margin except as a spot on one side of 
<specimenCount id="B1EDFD1DFF85FF899558FE6ED89137A7" box="[863,1001,486,507]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
). It is possible that 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8994C4FD88D80A344A" box="[707,882,512,534]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chuckbellamyi">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8994C4FD88D80A344A" box="[707,882,512,534]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. chuckbellamyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8995ABFD88DF3B344A" authorityName="Nelson" authorityYear="1994" box="[940,1091,512,534]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubrovittata">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8995ABFD88DF3B344A" box="[940,1091,512,534]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">A. rubrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represent clinal extremes of a single species distributed broadly from southeastern Arizona to southern 
<collectingCountry id="DFFC7604FF85FF8994C4FDD8D8693439" box="[707,785,592,613]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Mexico</collectingCountry>
; however, without comparable material from the wide intervening area it seems reasonable for now to regard them as distinct species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EFF1651FFF85FF8A94DCFD28DAC23253" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="A7543694FF85FF8A94DCFD28DAC23253" blockId="1.[707,1194,194,853]" lastBlockId="2.[151,639,194,1225]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8994DCFD28D84834E9" bold="true" box="[731,816,672,693]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Ecology.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="78508836FF85FF89956BFD28D8ED34E9" box="[876,917,672,693]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">type</typeStatus>
specimen was collected on flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899536FD32D8E7348C" box="[817,927,698,720]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Aloysia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899536FD32D801348C" box="[817,889,698,720]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Aloysia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8995A9FD33DF53348C" box="[942,1067,699,720]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Verbenaceae</taxonomicName>
) just east of the Atascosa Lookout Trailhead (
<figureCitation id="3FD02A11FF85FF89920DFD5DDF3E34B6" box="[1034,1094,725,746]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[731,772,1567,1586]" captionTargetBox="[707,1193,909,1543]" captionTargetId="figure-502@1.[707,1193,909,1543]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 2–3. 2) GoogleEarth map portion of southeastern Arizona, USA showing type locality of Acmaeodera chuckbellamyi (31.405°, −111.147°) in relation to the Atascosa Lookout Trailhead; 3) Habitat ∼0.5 mi W of Atascosa Lookout Trailhead. Note abundance of Alyosia sp. shrubs in draw. Photographed 25 August 2007 by P. Kaufman." pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) by Mike Arduser, a hymenopterist who was collecting bees from the flowers. Mr. Arduser (
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899207FC82DF45357C" box="[1024,1085,778,800]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">in litt.</emphasis>
) described the locality as grasslands with 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF89920EFCADDF033566" box="[1033,1147,805,827]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Aloysia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF89920EFCADDF2C3567" box="[1033,1108,805,827]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Aloysia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF8994C4FCB7D8103509" box="[707,872,831,853]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Eysenhardtia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8994C4FCB7D83B3509" box="[707,835,831,853]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Eysenhardtia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899570FCC8D8AC3509" box="[887,980,832,853]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
) shrubs in the draws and 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A96C2FF4ADA45368B" box="[197,317,194,216]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A96C2FF4ADA6F3684" box="[197,279,194,216]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Quercus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A974AFF4ADAD4368B" authorityName="Dumortier" authorityYear="1829" box="[333,428,194,215]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fagaceae</taxonomicName>
) trees at the foot of the slope. He also noted that the habitat was rockier and drier further up the trail but still supported 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A9690FE99DA79377B" box="[151,257,273,295]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Aloysia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A9690FE99DBA5377B" box="[151,221,273,295]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Aloysia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
shrubs that were in flower and attracting nectar-feeding insects such as bees, wasps, flies, and beetles. Mr. Arduser reported that there was no evidence of fire at the time of his visit. In early 
<date id="D3551054FF86FF8A96F6FEF4DA0A37CD" box="[241,370,380,401]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" value="2007-08">August 2007</date>
and again later that same month, Paul Kaufman visited the locality and reported (
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A96F0FE39DA4C379B" box="[247,308,433,455]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">in litt.</emphasis>
) that he did not find 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A9415FE39D906379A" box="[530,638,433,455]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Aloysia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A9415FE39D921379B" box="[530,601,433,455]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Aloysia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
shrubs at the Atascosa Lookout Trailhead, but that he did find them a short distance (
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A97E8FE6EDA8537A0" box="[495,509,486,508]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">∼</emphasis>
<quantity id="60139B71FF86FF8A97FAFE6ED93B37A7" box="[509,579,486,507]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" unit="km" value="0.8">0.8 km</quantity>
) west along Ruby Road (
<figureCitation id="3FD02A11FF86FF8A9740FD89DA07344A" box="[327,383,513,534]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[731,772,1567,1586]" captionTargetBox="[707,1193,909,1543]" captionTargetId="figure-502@1.[707,1193,909,1543]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 2–3. 2) GoogleEarth map portion of southeastern Arizona, USA showing type locality of Acmaeodera chuckbellamyi (31.405°, −111.147°) in relation to the Atascosa Lookout Trailhead; 3) Habitat ∼0.5 mi W of Atascosa Lookout Trailhead. Note abundance of Alyosia sp. shrubs in draw. Photographed 25 August 2007 by P. Kaufman." pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). The plants were in flower at this second locality, and nectar-feeding insects were plentiful; however, no 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A97A2FDBDD9323417" box="[421,586,565,587]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A97A2FDBDD9633417" box="[421,539,565,587]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Acmaeodera</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
were observed on the flowers. At the Atascosa Lookout Trailhead, the only flower-visiting buprestid observed was 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A972CFD0DDA4534E9" authority="Laporte and Gory, 1835" authorityName="Laporte and Gory" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubronotata">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A972CFD0DD95F34C7" box="[299,551,645,667]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Acmaeodera rubronotata</emphasis>
Laporte and Gory, 1835
</taxonomicName>
on flowers of an undetermined aster. Mr. Kaufman noted that the area appeared to have been burned in a prior year. In late 
<date id="D3551054FF86FF8A941CFD5DD90234B6" box="[539,634,725,746]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" value="2008-07">July 2008</date>
, Rick Westcott visited the area, reporting (
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A943DFD78D90F355A" box="[570,631,752,774]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">in litt.</emphasis>
) that he could not find 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A9779FC82DA933543" box="[382,491,778,800]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Aloysia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A9779FC82DABD357C" box="[382,453,778,800]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Aloysia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
shrubs or any other flowers suitable for 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A9793FCADD9723567" authorityName="Eschscholtz" authorityYear="1829" box="[404,522,805,827]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A9793FCADD9723567" box="[404,522,805,827]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Acmaeodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and repeating Mr. Kaufman’ s earlier observation that the area appeared to have burned in a prior year. In 
<date id="D3551054FF86FF8A9690FCFDDB8F35D6" box="[151,247,885,906]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" value="2011-06">June 2011</date>
, the area was burned by the 27,550-hectare Murphy Fire. This large fire significantly affected the 
<typeStatus id="78508836FF86FF8A96C5FC22DB9535E3" box="[194,237,938,959]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">type</typeStatus>
locality and surrounding areas, completely killing stands of pinyon pine and juniper at higher elevations along the Atascosa Lookout Trail (tinyurl.com/mqwkhm9).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="F394661CFF85FF8994DCF997D854309D" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" startId="1.[731,772,1567,1586]" targetBox="[707,1193,909,1543]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph id="A7543694FF85FF8994DCF997D854309D" blockId="1.[707,1193,1566,1729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8994DCF997D81B306E" bold="true" box="[731,867,1566,1586]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Figs. 2–3. 2)</emphasis>
GoogleEarth map portion of southeastern Arizona, USA showing type locality of 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF899245F9BED839303D" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Acmaeodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chuckbellamyi">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF899245F9BED839303D" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Acmaeodera chuckbellamyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(31.405°, 
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8995A3F9C6D8C8303D" box="[932,944,1614,1633]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">−</emphasis>
111.147°) in relation to the Atascosa Lookout Trailhead; 
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF8995CDF9EED8A53025" bold="true" box="[970,989,1638,1657]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">3)</emphasis>
Habitat 
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF89922AF9EEDF413025" box="[1069,1081,1638,1657]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">∼</emphasis>
0.5 mi W of Atascosa Lookout Trailhead. Note abundance of 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF85FF89926CF9F6D9A430F5" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Alyosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF85FF89926CF9F6DFD130CD" box="[1131,1193,1662,1681]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Alyosia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
shrubs in draw. Photographed 25 August 2007 by P. Kaufman.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="EFF1651FFF86FF8A96A8FB9CDA6A3295" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A7543694FF86FF8A96A8FB9CDA6A3295" blockId="2.[151,639,194,1225]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="959FEA86FF86FF8A96A8FB9CDA5A3275" bold="true" box="[175,290,1044,1065]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Etymology.</emphasis>
I take great pleasure in naming this species in honor of the late Charles “Chuck” Bellamy. Chuck was a consummate student of 
<taxonomicName id="60EB4D17FF86FF8A9690FBECDA743225" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[151,268,1124,1145]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Buprestidae</taxonomicName>
and my friend and mentor. During our 20-year friendship, I marveled at his productivity, heeded his sage counsel, and savored his cerebral wit.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
